The predictor variable will be the life rating while the response variable will be the gratitude score. Each group in the study was given a different task to do each week, and the goal of that study was to see if there is an association between each persons life rating and its overall gratitude score based on each group.

gf_boxplot(group ~ gratitude_score, data = gratitude) %>%
  gf_labs(x = 'Gratitude Score',
          y = 'Group')

This graph shows the mean gratitude score for each group and where the distribution of the responses lie. From this we can see that the gratitude group has a higher mean of gratitude score. The events group and the hassles group have a pretty similar result to each other.

gf_point(life_rating ~ gratitude_score, data = gratitude, color = ~group) %>%
  gf_labs(x = 'Gratitude Score',
          y = ' Life Rating') %>%
  gf_lm()

gf_point(life_rating ~ gratitude_score, data = gratitude) %>%
  gf_lm()

The adjusted R-squared = 0.00377. R-squared tells us how well the model fits the line. Since R-squared is low, the line does not fit the model well.

gratitude <- gratitude %>%
  mutate(resid = resid(slr),
         pred = predict(slr))
gf_point(resid ~ pred, data = gratitude) %>%
  gf_labs(title = 'Lack of non-Linearity',
       x = 'Perdictors',
          y = 'Rediduals') %>%
  gf_lm()

This graph shows the lack of non-linearity. There is no trend and passes the test.

s245::gf_acf(~slr) %>%
  gf_lims(y = c(-1,1)) %>%
  gf_labs(title = 'Independance of Residuals')

This test shows the independence of the residuals, and the residuals all stay within the confidence bounds which means it passes the test.

gf_point(life_rating ~ gratitude_score, data = gratitude) %>%
  gf_line(pred ~ gratitude_score) %>%
  gf_labs(title = 'Prediction Plot',
          x = 'Gratitude Score',
          y = 'Life Rating')

ANALYZE First, looking at the box plot, we see that mean of the gratitude score was higher than the other groups in the study. However, looking at the line plot that was comparing the gratitude score to life rating based on group, we could see that the hassles group had a more positive correlation between the two variables in that graph. The higher the gratitude score, the higher the life rating. The linear regression shows a small correlation between Gratitude score and Life Rating. It passes the independence test and lack of non-linearity, and for the sake of this analysis, I am going to assume it passes the normal distribution of residuals and the error variance constant tests. Since it passes the LINE tests it is appropriate to fit a line to the data. The slope of the linear regression is 0.08 which shows a weak correlation between gratitude score and life rating. To answer the question if the gratitude score is associated with the group, the gratitude score is higher in the gratitude group, however the goal of this study is to see if a habit of gratitude can improve mental and physical health and in turn lead to improvements in their life. Interpreting the linear regression with this in mind, there is weak correlation which means that gratitude could lead to improved life ratings, but we would need more data to reinforce this as the evidence is weak.
